"""
WIRING ReduceLROnPlateau INTO neural_ode_mod.py  (3 surgical edits)

Goal: let the LR decay when val_loss plateaus, which is exactly the failure
mode in the glide log (val_loss flat ~1.40 for ~190 epochs before early-stop).
The framework already has ReduceLROnPlateauConfiguration; the missing piece is
that NODEPredictor.fit never STEPS a scheduler. These edits add an optional
scheduler that fit steps each epoch on val_loss, gated so every existing model
(no scheduler set) behaves byte-for-byte as before.

Design choice: rather than change _initialize_optimizer's contract or the
config types, we add an optional `self.scheduler` attribute (default None).
fit steps it only if set. train_NEXT creates and assigns it per stage. This
keeps the blast radius to three tiny, reversible additions.

================================================================================
EDIT 1 of 3  —  NODEPredictor.__init__
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Add a default scheduler attribute. Place it right after `self.aug_dim = aug_dim`
(or anywhere in __init__ after super().__init__()):

    APPLY-> add this one line:

        self.scheduler: torch.optim.lr_scheduler.LRScheduler | None = None

Why: gives fit something to check. Defaults to None => no behaviour change for
any model that doesn't set it.

================================================================================
EDIT 2 of 3  —  NODEPredictor.fit, inside the epoch loop
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step the scheduler once per epoch, AFTER val metrics are computed and BEFORE
the early-stopper check, using the same metric the early stopper watches
(val_loss), with a fallback to train loss if val is absent.

Locate this existing block near the end of the epoch loop in fit():

        self._add_metrics_to_global_metrics(metrics)
        self._log_metrics(metrics, iteration=epoch)

    APPLY-> insert the following BETWEEN _log_metrics and the checkpoint/early-stop block:

            # --- LR scheduler step (ReduceLROnPlateau) -------------------
            # Only active when train_NEXT assigned a scheduler for this stage.
            # Step on the early-stopper metric (val_loss) so the LR drops when
            # validation plateaus; fall back to train loss if val is absent.
            if self.scheduler is not None:
                _watch_key = self.early_stopper.metric_name if self.early_stopper is not None else "loss"
                _watch = metrics.get(_watch_key, metrics.get("loss"))
                # ReduceLROnPlateau.step wants a python float
                _watch_val = _watch.item() if hasattr(_watch, "item") else float(_watch)
                self.scheduler.step(_watch_val)
                # surface the current LR so it shows up in the logs/metrics
                _cur_lr = self.optimizer.param_groups[0]["lr"]
                metrics["lr"] = torch.tensor(_cur_lr)

Notes:
  * Insert it INSIDE `for epoch in range(...)`, at the same indentation level
    as `self._add_metrics_to_global_metrics(metrics)`.
  * Putting it before _add_metrics... vs after only changes whether "lr" is in
    the persisted metric history for that epoch; inserting AFTER _log_metrics
    (as above) keeps it out of the per-epoch console line but still steps
    correctly. If you WANT lr in the console line, instead insert the block
    BEFORE _add_metrics_to_global_metrics.
  * metrics["lr"] is a tensor so _add_metrics_to_global_metrics's .detach()
    (if it ever sees it) won't crash — matching the tensor-typed convention.

================================================================================
EDIT 3 of 3  —  train_NEXT, per-stage setup in the length-strategy loop
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Create and assign the scheduler after the optimizer is (re)initialized for each
stage, and clear it on stages where you don't want decay. The optimizer is
rebuilt per stage by `node._initialize_optimizer()`, so the scheduler must be
created AFTER that call (it needs the fresh optimizer).

Locate, inside the `for len_strat in length_strategies:` loop:

            # Setup the model for training and inference.
            node._initialize_optimizer()

            # reset the early stop check
            node.early_stopper = early_stopper

    APPLY-> insert AFTER `node._initialize_optimizer()` (and after early_stopper
            is set, so we can size patience relative to it):

            # --- per-stage LR scheduler -----------------------------------
            # Attach a ReduceLROnPlateau ONLY to the long full-trajectory
            # stages, where the glide log showed val_loss plateauing for ~190
            # epochs before early-stop. Patience MUST be shorter than the
            # early-stopper's patience, or the run stops before the LR can drop.
            from lm_ai_torch_training.lr_schedulers.reduce_on_plateau import (
                ReduceLROnPlateauConfiguration,
            )
            if data_fraction == 1.0:
                sched_patience = max(1, early_stopper.patience // 2)   # < early-stop patience
                node.scheduler = ReduceLROnPlateauConfiguration(
                    early_stop_metric_name,        # "val_loss"
                    factor=0.5,
                    patience=sched_patience,
                    min_lr=1e-7,
                    threshold=1e-4,
                ).create_from_optimizer(node.optimizer)
            else:
                node.scheduler = None              # no decay on the short curriculum stages

Why these settings:
  * factor=0.5  — halve the LR on plateau (gentle; 0.1 is torch default but too
    aggressive when stacked with the curriculum's own LR resets).
  * patience = early_stopper.patience // 2  — guarantees at least one LR drop
    BEFORE early stop can trigger. Your 1.0 stages use EarlyStopper patience 50,
    so scheduler patience ~25: the LR will halve after 25 flat epochs, giving
    the model 25 more (now at half LR) to improve before early-stop at 50.
  * min_lr=1e-7  — matches the floor your final curriculum stage already uses.
  * Restricting to data_fraction==1.0 targets exactly the plateau you observed
    and leaves the (working) short-horizon stages untouched.

================================================================================
SANITY EXPECTATIONS AFTER APPLYING
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  * Short stages (0.1..0.7): identical behaviour to now (scheduler is None).
  * Long 1.0 stages: watch val_loss flatten, then LR halve ~25 epochs later;
    val_loss should take a fresh step down after each halving. If it doesn't
    drop at all after several halvings, the plateau is a capacity/data ceiling,
    not an LR problem — and that's useful signal too.
  * If a 1.0 stage has NO validation data for some reason, the step falls back
    to train "loss" so it won't KeyError.
